On 16 January, Egypt's [[CASE 30|EGX]] stock market index fell on speculation the instability would spread.<ref>{{cite web|last=Namatalla |first=Ahmed A |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-16/egypt-stocks-drop-most-in-six-weeks-as-tunisia-s-leader-ben-ali-overthrown.html |title=Egypt Stocks Drop Most in Six Weeks on Concern Tunisia Unrest May Spread |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2011-01-16 |accessdate=2011-01-26}}</ref> Protests in Egypt then also led to a restaurant owner, Abdou Abdel-Moneim Jaafara, setting himself on fire. On 18 January, two other self-immolations, one by a lawyer in Cairo and another by an unemployed 25-year-old in Alexandria, were reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12214090 |title=Egyptian man dies after setting himself alight |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-01-19 |accessdate=2011-01-26}}</ref> Many Egyptians have set up ''Facebook'' pages calling for 25 January, Egypt's 'National Police Day' to be "a day of revolution against torture, poverty, corruption and unemployment.".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12204999|title=Man sets himself on fire in Cairo protest}}</ref>
